3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"dYdX V4 calculates funding rates every hour using the time-weighted average premium between perpetual and index prices over the preceding period. Unlike centralized exchanges, funding payments occur entirely on-chain through the Cosmos appchain's validator network. The decentralized architecture means funding rates reflect pure market dynamics without exchange intervention, while the hourly frequency provides more granular arbitrage opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","AVAX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX/USDT on dYdX attracts funding arbitrage due to AVAX's significant institutional adoption and DeFi ecosystem activity driving price volatility. The pair's large trading volume ensures tight spreads and reliable funding rate calculations, while AVAX's correlation with broader Layer 1 narratives creates predictable funding patterns during market cycles."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX/USDT funding rates on dYdX typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% per hour during normal market conditions. Bull markets often see sustained positive funding as long positions dominate, particularly during AVAX ecosystem announcements or subnet launches. Bear markets frequently produce negative funding as shorts pile in, especially during broader Layer 1 selloffs. The hourly intervals create more frequent rate adjustments compared to traditional exchanges, reducing extreme funding spikes but requiring more active monitoring for arbitrage strategies."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The primary arbitrage strategy involves exploiting funding differentials between dYdX's hourly cycles and other exchanges' 8-hour schedules. Traders can capture multiple small funding payments on dYdX while holding opposite positions on traditional exchanges with longer intervals. Cross-DEX arbitrage opportunities arise when dYdX's decentralized rate discovery differs from centralized exchanges during high volatility periods. The Cosmos appchain's sovereignty allows for unique funding dynamics that often diverge from Ethereum-based perpetuals, creating additional arbitrage windows."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"dYdX V4's post-migration lower liquidity compared to major CEXs can create wider spreads during volatile periods, impacting arbitrage profitability. The Cosmos appchain introduces bridge risks when moving funds between ecosystems for cross-exchange strategies. Smart contract risks exist despite audits, as the V4 migration represents significant architectural changes from the previous StarkEx-based system. Funding arbitrage positions face liquidation risk if AVAX price moves significantly against leveraged positions, particularly given AVAX's higher volatility compared to major cryptocurrencies."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are AVAX/USDT funding payments made on dYdX?","answer":"dYdX V4 makes funding payments every hour for AVAX/USDT perpetuals, unlike most exchanges that use 8-hour cycles. This creates more frequent but smaller funding payments, offering additional arbitrage opportunities for active traders."},{"question":"What's the typical funding rate range for AVAX/USDT on dYdX?","answer":"AVAX/USDT funding rates typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% per hour during normal conditions. During high volatility or strong directional moves, rates can exceed 0.1% per hour, creating significant arbitrage opportunities."},{"question":"How does dYdX V4's Cosmos appchain affect AVAX funding rates?","answer":"The Cosmos appchain provides sovereign rate discovery independent of Ethereum gas costs and MEV, potentially creating funding rate differentials versus other chains. This architectural difference can produce unique arbitrage opportunities when dYdX rates diverge from other platforms."},{"question":"What are the main risks of funding arbitrage with AVAX on dYdX?","answer":"Key risks include lower post-migration liquidity creating wider spreads, bridge risks when moving funds between Cosmos and other chains, and AVAX's inherent volatility potentially causing liquidations. Smart contract risks also exist with the new V4 architecture despite extensive auditing."}]}]
